  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the books to improve English?",
  "response": "Improving your English can involve a variety of resources depending on your specific goals, such as vocabulary, grammar, writing, or reading comprehension. Here are some recommended books across different categories that could help:\n\n### Vocabulary and Grammar\n1. **\"English Grammar in Use\" by Raymond Murphy** - A self-study reference and practice book suitable for intermediate learners.\n2. **\"Word Power Made Easy\" by Norman Lewis** - A vocabulary-building book that focuses on root words and provides exercises to reinforce learning.\n3. **\"The Elements of Style\" by William Strunk Jr. and E.B. White** - A guide to writing style and English usage that emphasizes clarity and conciseness.\n\n### Reading Comprehension\n4. **\"Reading Comprehension Made Easy\" by Rebecca K. Mcclain** - This book offers strategies and techniques for improving reading skills.\n5. **\"A Short History of Nearly Everything\" by Bill Bryson** - Engaging prose that can help improve comprehension while providing knowledge about science and history.\n\n### Writing\n6. **\"On Writing: A Memoir of the Craft\" by Stephen King** - A blend of memoir and writing advice that is both entertaining and informative.\n7. **\"Writing Down the Bones: Freeing the Writer Within\" by Natalie Goldberg** - This book encourages creative writing and can help improve your writing skills through practice.\n\n### Conversation and Listening\n8. **\"Practice Makes Perfect: English Conversation\" by Jean Yates** - This book provides practical exercises and dialogues to improve conversational skills.\n9. **\"English Idioms in Use\" by Michael McCarthy and Felicity O'Dell** - A resource for understanding commonly used idioms to help in conversation and comprehension.\n\n### Literature\n10. **Classic novels** like \"Pride and Prejudice\" by Jane Austen or \"The Great Gatsby\" by F. Scott Fitzgerald. Reading literature can enhance vocabulary and provide cultural context.\n11. **\"The Catcher in the Rye\" by J.D. Salinger** - A novel that is often recommended for its accessible language and themes relevant to youth.\n\n### Additional Resources\n- **\"Word Power Made Easy\" by Norman Lewis** for vocabulary expansion.\n- **Online platforms** (like Grammarly, Duolingo, or language exchange platforms) that complement your book learning with interactive exercises.\n\n### Note\nChoosing the right books can depend on your current proficiency level and learning objectives. Start with material that is slightly above your current level; this will challenge you without causing frustration. Happy learning!",
